 <h3 class="title" id="post-75242">
  <a href="https://blogs.ei.columbia.edu/2019/03/07/greenland-rain-ice-melting/" rel="bookmark" title="It’s Raining on the Greenland Ice. In the Winter.">
   It’s Raining on the Greenland Ice. In the Winter.
  </a>
 </h3>
 <div class="excerpt">
  <p>
   Rainy weather is becoming increasingly common over parts of the Greenland ice sheet, triggering sudden melting events that are eating at the ice and priming the surface for more widespread future melting, says a new study.
  </p>
 </div>
 <div class="author-time">
  <span class="author">
   by
   <a href="https://blogs.ei.columbia.edu/author/kevin-krajick/" rel="author" title="Posts by Kevin Krajick">
    Kevin Krajick
   </a>
  </span>
  <span class="separator">
   |
  </span>
  <span class="time">
   March 7, 2019
